title: For Sale:  Winchester 1895 Takedown .30-06, Mfg. 1915       Another Great Winchester From Jackson Armory!
postcontent: Winchester 1895 Takedown Rifle, .30-06, Mfg. 1915. Stock # MSR243615RT. Serial # 776xx. One of several hundred collectible military, antique, sporting, custom, and tactical firearms, as well as edged weapons and militaria we have for sale at Jackson Armory (see our other listings), this is one of several lever-action Winchesters we have is stock. This is another Winchester for the Advanced Collector – a Model 1895 Takedown Rifle, made in 1915, and chambered for .30-06. The Model 1895 was the last Winchester designed by John Browning, and it was the first to feature a box magazine. This is a nice example – about 85% of the original blue on the barrel, receiver in the white with mild freckling, and absolutely gorgeous wooden stocks, sanded and varnihjed with only mild service marks – a 85-90% gun overall with a crisp bore, smooth operating lever action and a smooth trigger pull. You will want to prominently display this rifle, it will be one of the gems of your collection!

postcontent:
Allied Armament had done the conversion into 308 Cal.

The M1919 Browning is a .30 caliber medium machine gun that was widely used during the 20th century. It was used as a light infantry, coaxial, mounted, aircraft, and anti-aircraft machine gun by the U.S. and many other countries, especially during World War II, the Korean War, and the Vietnam War. Although it began to be superseded by newer designs in the later half of the century (such as by the M60 machine gun), it remained in use in many North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) countries and elsewhere for much longer. It is very similar in design to the larger .50 caliber (12.7mm) M2 Machine Gun, which is also a Browning-designed weapon and is still in NATO service. Many M1919s were rechambered for the new 7.62Ã—51mm NATO round and served into the 1990s, as well as up to the present day in some countries. The United States Navy also converted many to 7.62mm NATO, and designated them Mk 21 Mod 0; they were commonly used on river craft in the 1960s and 1970s in Vietnam. The M1919 was an air-cooled development of the standard US machine gun of World War I, the Browning M1917, as designed by John M. Browning
